{
  "card_id": "previous_day_high_low",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Previous Day High / Low",
  "aliases": [
    "PDH",
    "PDL"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "The high and low of the prior trading day, used as draw-on-liquidity targets or reversal points. Unless price is consolidating, it tends to reach for one or both of these levels during the next day's session. In trending contexts, price often draws to these levels; a sweep and rejection can signal a reversal.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "On the daily chart, locate the high and low of the previous complete trading day's candlestick.",
    "Extend these levels horizontally into the current trading day as horizontal reference lines.",
    "Optionally, look back up to 3 trading days to mark multiple previous day highs/lows for confluence zones.",
    "Assess whether price is consolidating or directional; if directional, anticipate a move toward the previous day's high or low.",
    "In an uptrend, price repeatedly touches or breaks the previous day high; in a downtrend, price repeatedly touches or breaks the previous day low.",
    "When price fails to break the previous day high, it indicates a bearish bias; failure to break the previous day low indicates a bullish bias.",
    "Observe whether price consolidates within the previous day high/low range or breaks and closes outside the range (a mere touch is insufficient to confirm direction).",
    "These horizontal levels remain valid as reference levels on lower timeframes (e.g., 1-hour, 5-minute)."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "Previous day high/low serves as an initial liquidity target or reversal zone. In trending contexts, price often draws to these levels; a sweep and rejection can signal a reversal. They are used to frame entries and set targets, especially when aligned with higher-timeframe bias and session analysis. Price breaking and closing outside the range suggests trend continuation. Combine with displacement, failure to break, and session liquidity to frame reversal or continuation bias, and to set stop-loss or profit targets.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Assuming a trade opportunity exists every day — even with clear previous day high/low targets, a valid entry may not materialize.",
    "Ignoring the importance of displacement — judging bias solely on previous day high/low without considering whether price successfully breaks the level.",
    "Failing to distinguish between price touching and closing outside the range — a mere touch is insufficient to confirm direction; a close outside is required.",
    "Assuming price will inevitably reach the previous day high/low when not in consolidation, overlooking the exception of consolidation phases.",
    "Confusing previous day high/low with the current day's high/low or opening price, leading to incorrect reference levels.",
    "Confusing previous day high/low with session high/low, leading to incorrect liquidity target identification.",
    "Failing to mark previous day high/low across multiple timeframes, losing reference on lower timeframes.",
    "Over-relying on previous day high/low while ignoring other structures — should combine with FVG, Order Block, Swing Points, and other liquidity levels for confirmation.",
    "Expecting price to reach the previous day high/low during consolidation phases when no directional expansion is signaled.",
    "Treating every touch as an automatic reversal without confirmation from displacement or market structure shift."
  ],
